<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900411-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>900411-0010.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GORBACHEV RAISED the possibility of imposing direct ruleover Lithuania.   As the president of the breakaway Baltic republic blamed&quot;ultra-rightist&quot; forces for Moscow's threat to useunspecified political and economic measures againstLithuania, the Soviet leader warned that he might imposedirect presidential rule in the event of &quot;civilian conflictor confrontation.&quot; Such a step could include martial law anddissolving the republic's legislature. Gorbachev, who notedthat Lithuania's independence bid could be costly tointernational peace, also said that the Kremlin was stillstriving to find a political solution to the situation.</LP><TEXT>   With opposition expected to a planned economic package,Gorbachev said his advisory council would meet Saturday todiscuss speeding market changes.   ---   Palestinian extremists in Beirut freed a French woman, aBelgian man and their young daughter after holding themhostage for more than two years. The three were taken toParis following their release by a Libyan-backed group headedby Abu Nidal. The move came a month after France returnedthree jet fighters to Gadhafi.   ---   Walesa confirmed that he would run for Poland's presidencyin the country's next elections, according to the state-ownedPAP news agency. A top aide to the Solidarity founder saidWalesa was prepared to force President Jaruzelski to resignbecause of the slow pace of political and economic change,Reuters news agency reported.   ---   NASA scrubbed the launch of the space shuttle Discoveryand said it could be as long as two weeks before a newattempt to carry the $1.5 billion Hubble Space Telescope intoorbit. Space agency officials at Cape Canaveral in Floridasaid the countdown was halted by a faulty power unit in thespacecraft's steering system.   ---   Bush said there is &quot;an awful lot to be done&quot; to resolveU.S.-Soviet arms-control differences before next month'ssuperpower summit. The president, in Canada for a meetingwith Prime Minister Mulroney, also said that &quot;should thingsdeteriorate in Lithuania, it would be extraordinarilydifficult&quot; for U.S.-Soviet ties to improve quickly.   ---   Federal safety officials concluded that lapses by BoeingCo., United Airlines and the FAA contributed to the February1989 failure of a cargo door on a jetliner over the PacificOcean. The resulting decompression caused several feet ofcabin floor to collapse, sending nine passengers to theirdeaths.   ---   East German legislators haggled over unfilled cabinetposts, delaying an agreement on East Europe's first freelyelected coalition. The last-minute wrangling reportedlycentered on the post of economic minister, who would play acrucial role in the nation's change to a free-market systemand in its reunification with West Germany.   ---   Greece's Mitsotakis was designated premier and asked bythe president to form a new government. The conservativeleader, whose New Democracy party won 150 seats in the300-member legislature in Sunday's nationwide elections,secured the backing of a centrist deputy for a majority.   ---   Health researchers have discovered new evidence linkingstress on the job to high blood pressure. The study foundthat men who hold jobs with demands over which they havelittle control are more likely to have high blood pressureand to sustain physical changes to the heart than men whodon't face such strains.   ---   India's prime minister said the country should be&quot;psychologically prepared&quot; for an armed conflict withPakistan over the disputed Kashmir valley. Singh made hisremarks in New Delhi's Parliament after Moslem secessionistsin the valley killed a Hindu industrialist held since Friday.   ---   Western travelers in Beijing said two envoys sent lastweek to calm Islamic unrest in China's remote northwest werekilled. Security forces reportedly killed about 50 people insubsequent riots. Regional officials have declined to commenton the reports.   ---   The Census Bureau reported that the number of men in theU.S. grew faster than the population of women in the 1980s,something that hasn't happened since the first decade of thecentury. Death rates for men declined more rapidly than forwomen, but the report showed that women continue to outnumbermen in the country.   ---   Mongolia's Communist Party opened a meeting in Ulan Batorwith an appeal for political and economic restructuring in anattempt to maintain its 70-year-old grip on power amidgrowing pro-democracy demands. The three-day meeting comesahead of planned multiparty elections.   ---   Mandela will lead an 11-member African National Congressdelegation in talks next month with the government onblack-white power sharing. Following the May 2-4 discussions,the black nationalist leader will embark on a series offoreign trips, including stops in the U.S. and the SovietUnion.</TEXT></DOC>